The Asian Development Bank warned of the potential devastating impact of a large-scale food epidemic in China, citing past events like the 2008 Beijing Olympics.
Tainted food affects over 300 million Chinese annually, posing a significant health and economic risk.
Recent reports highlight ongoing food safety concerns in China, prompting increased government scrutiny and response measures.
The country has faced numerous food safety issues, from contaminated pork to parasite-infested snails, underscoring the urgent need for comprehensive supervision across the entire food production process.
Efforts are underway to strengthen food safety regulations and enforcement to protect public health and restore consumer confidence.
